[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per actively-coordinated member per month (depends on care-journey complexity, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, EHR-integration depth, referral-tracking integration depth, and care-management overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret is 68. Margaret has type 2 diabetes (diagnosed 11 years ago), heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (diagnosed two years ago after a hospitalization that nobody in the family talks about), chronic kidney disease stage 3b, mild cognitive impairment that her family has noticed but her primary care physician has not yet formally documented, hypertension, and a remote history of breast cancer (in remission for nine years, with annual surveillance still active). Margaret takes nine medications. Margaret sees seven clinicians: her primary care physician, her cardiologist (heart failure), her endocrinologist (diabetes), her nephrologist (CKD), her oncologist (annual surveillance), her ophthalmologist (diabetic retinopathy screening), and a clinical pharmacist who runs medication-therapy-management visits twice a year. Margaret was referred to a vascular surgeon eight weeks ago after her cardiologist noticed a finding on a routine echo; Margaret is not sure if she scheduled that appointment, and the cardiologist's office assumes she did. Margaret was discharged from a brief hospitalization seven weeks ago for a heart-failure exacerbation; the discharge summary said "follow up with cardiology within seven days and primary care within fourteen days," and Margaret saw her cardiologist eleven days later (because that was the soonest available) and has not yet seen her primary care physician (because the schedule was full and Margaret meant to call back but did not).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret's daughter Jen lives in another state and calls Margaret three times a week. Jen is the family's de facto care coordinator. Jen has a spreadsheet on her laptop labeled "Mom" with twelve tabs: medications, providers, appointments, lab results that Mom has remembered to share, insurance information, the discharge instructions from the hospitalization, the names and phone numbers of nurses Jen has spoken to in the past, the prior-authorization status for a medication that took three months to get approved, and four other tabs that have not been updated in a while. Jen knows about the vascular surgery referral because she saw the after-visit summary in the patient portal; Jen does not know that Margaret has not scheduled the appointment. Jen knows about the discharge instructions because Jen drove to her mother's house for the discharge; Jen does not know that the primary care follow-up has not happened.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret's primary care physician knows that Margaret is a complex patient and tries to coordinate the care, but the primary care physician's clinic has 2,200 patients per primary care provider, the EHR's care-coordination tooling is mostly designed for in-clinic workflow, the cardiologist's notes arrive in the EHR's inbox with a forty-eight-to-ninety-six-hour delay, the endocrinologist's notes arrive in a different format because the endocrinologist is in a different health system, the nephrologist's notes arrive on paper because the nephrologist is in a small practice that has not yet exchanged information through the regional HIE, and the oncologist's notes arrive on a different patient portal that Margaret has the login for and the primary care physician does not. The primary care physician has a care manager assigned to the practice; the care manager carries 180 patients and triages by acuity. Margaret was last actively touched by the care manager four months ago, when the heart-failure exacerbation triggered a flag.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What happens, in practice, is the kind of thing that happens to Margaret. The vascular-surgery referral does not get scheduled because nobody in Margaret's life is specifically responsible for closing that loop, and Margaret cannot remember whether she scheduled it or whether she meant to. The primary care follow-up after the discharge does not happen because the schedule was full and the call-back did not happen. Three of Margaret's medications interact in a way that her cardiologist did not flag (the cardiologist did not have visibility into the prescription the endocrinologist added two weeks ago, and the prescribing endocrinologist did not know about a recent dose change the cardiologist made). Margaret's last A1c was checked seven months ago and is overdue; her last comprehensive metabolic panel was four months ago and is overdue per the CKD monitoring protocol; her annual eye exam for diabetic retinopathy was eighteen months ago and is overdue. Margaret's daughter Jen knows about most but not all of this, and updates the spreadsheet when she remembers. The primary care physician's care manager has Margaret on a list of "patients to circle back to" but has not gotten there yet because there are forty patients ahead of her on that list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Then something happens. Margaret has a fall in her bathroom on a Tuesday afternoon. Margaret calls Jen. Jen drives down. The local emergency department admits Margaret for observation, finds nothing acute, but the hospitalist notices that Margaret has an unscheduled vascular-surgery referral, an overdue A1c, an overdue CMP, an overdue eye exam, a primary-care follow-up that did not happen, and a new soft-call medication concern from the pharmacist on staff. The hospitalist's note, transmitted to the EHR sixteen hours later, asks the question that the system has been asking for years: who is actually coordinating this patient's care?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The answer, in 2026 healthcare for medically-complex patients, is most often "nobody, and increasingly software."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the problem care coordination has had since coordinated care became a thing. Healthcare in the United States, and increasingly elsewhere, is delivered by specialty teams that are organizationally, operationally, technologically, and financially separated from each other. The patient is the integration point. The patient (and, if the patient is lucky, a family member) is responsible for closing the loops between specialists, scheduling the follow-ups, transmitting information that does not flow electronically, remembering the after-visit summaries, taking the medications correctly, getting the labs drawn, getting the imaging done, getting the referrals scheduled, and surfacing concerns to the right clinician at the right time. For uncomplicated patients with one condition and one or two clinicians, this works adequately most of the time. For medically-complex patients with five or more conditions, four or more clinicians, ten or more medications, and care plans that span hospitals and outpatient clinics and specialty providers and home-health visits, the integration burden exceeds what the patient and family can carry, and pieces fall through the cracks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cracks have specific costs. Medication-related adverse events from poorly-coordinated medication regimens. Avoidable readmissions because the discharge plan was not closed-the-loop. Missed cancer surveillance and missed diabetic retinopathy screening and missed CKD monitoring because the orders did not have an owner. Duplicate imaging because the receiving specialist did not know the prior imaging existed. Care delays because referrals are not scheduled or scheduled but not tracked. Patient and family burnout from managing a complexity that was never theirs to manage. Disparities in outcomes between patients with engaged family caregivers and patients without, between English-speaking patients and patients who prefer other languages, between patients with high health-literacy and patients with limited health-literacy, between patients with stable housing and reliable transportation and patients without. The patients who need the most coordination are typically the patients who are least equipped to provide it themselves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Healthcare has tried to solve this in several waves. The first wave, going back to the 1990s, was case management programs in payer organizations and (later) care management programs in provider organizations. These work, when they have adequate staffing, for the highest-acuity patients. The economics make it impractical to extend case management to all medically-complex patients; case managers carry caseloads of 80 to 200 patients, and the patients with the most need exceed the staffing available. The second wave was the patient-portal era: give patients access to their information through web and mobile apps, and let them coordinate themselves. The portals are useful but largely passive; they show information but do not actively close loops. Patients still have to remember to log in, look at the after-visit summary, schedule the follow-up, ask the question, and surface the concern. The third wave was workflow tooling for care managers: shared care plans in the EHR, referral-tracking systems, transition-of-care workflows. These help when staffed, but the staffing limit has not gone away. The fourth wave, the one this recipe is about, is conversational AI assistants that work alongside the patient (and the patient's family) and the care team to actively close coordination loops, surface concerns, track follow-up commitments, integrate information from multiple sources, and route to humans when the situation requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that helps medically-complex patients (and their family caregivers) navigate care coordination across multiple clinicians, multiple care episodes, multiple systems, and long time horizons. The bot tracks referrals from order to scheduled appointment to completed visit to closed loop. The bot tracks transitions of care (discharge from hospital to home, transfer between facilities, escalation from outpatient to inpatient, hand-back from specialist to primary care). The bot integrates information from the EHR, from the regional HIE, from the patient's stated history, from the family caregiver's input, and from the care team's notes. The bot answers care-coordination questions ("when is my next cardiology appointment?", "did I get the eye exam scheduled?", "what was my last A1c?", "what did the cardiologist recommend?", "is anyone going to call about the vascular surgery referral?"). The bot escalates to human care managers, primary care, and (where appropriate) specialists when the patient's situation calls for it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinical decision-maker. The bot does not adjust medication regimens. The bot does not provide diagnostic interpretation. The bot does not replace the patient's primary care physician or any of their specialists. The bot helps the patient and family track and execute the care plan that the clinical team has established; the bot does not establish the plan.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a replacement for care managers. The bot extends the reach of the institution's care-management workforce to the broader medically-complex population that case management cannot afford to staff. The bot handles the routine coordination touches; the care manager focuses on the cases that need human judgment, advocacy, escalation, and complex problem-solving.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chatbot in the FAQ sense. The bot has long-running context across months and years, integrates information from multiple data sources, tracks specific commitments and follow-ups across time, and has memory of the patient's care journey that is durable across episodes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinical record. The bot's longitudinal store augments rather than replaces the EHR. Where consent permits, the bot writes structured summaries back to the EHR (FHIR Communication, FHIR Task, FHIR CarePlan-related resources) so the care team has visibility into bot interactions; the source of truth for clinical content remains the EHR.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not for every patient. The bot is targeted at medically-complex patients who benefit from active coordination support: typically patients with three or more chronic conditions, four or more active medications, or a recent hospitalization or transition of care. Lower-complexity patients may not need active coordination; the bot's enrollment criteria reflect the population it is designed to serve.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters, not sprints. The EHR-integration work is multi-quarter, the multi-data-source integration work is multi-quarter, the care-team-workflow integration work is multi-quarter, and the outcome demonstration is multi-quarter to multi-year.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in the cleverness of its responses; the value is in the relentlessness of its loop-closing. A care coordination assistant that knows about a vascular-surgery referral and reliably reminds the patient to schedule it, knows about a primary-care follow-up that has not happened and reliably surfaces it, knows about an overdue A1c and reliably arranges the order, knows that the cardiologist made a medication change and reliably surfaces it to the endocrinologist, and knows that the patient's daughter has been on the spreadsheet for three years and reliably keeps the daughter in the loop, is a bot that does the unglamorous work the system has been failing to do, at scale, for the medically-complex population that has been falling through the cracks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into how it actually works.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
